#🧠 Repo-Mind: Local RAG Forensic Tool

**Repo-Mind** is a high-performance, local-first AI auditor designed for deep-dive forensic analysis of software repositories. Unlike standard AI assistants that only see the current state of code, Repo-Mind cross-references **Historical Git Intent** with **Active Source Code** to identify security regressions and architectural drift.

---

## 🚀 Key Features
* **Forensic Auditing:** Automatically compare historical bug fixes (Git Diffs) against current implementations to ensure critical patches haven't been reverted.
* **Hybrid Retrieval Engine:** A custom "Dual-Stream" RAG pipeline that balances historical commits and live source files using metadata-aware filtering (`hash: LATEST`).
* **Local & Private:** Powered by **Ollama**, ensuring your proprietary code and Git history never leave your local hardware.
* **High-Performance Telemetry:** Real-time monitoring of token throughput (30+ tok/s), latency, and system resource utilization.

---

## 📊 Performance Benchmarks
*Tested on: NVIDIA RTX 3050 (6GB VRAM) | Model: Qwen-2.5-Coder-7B*

| Metric | Result |
| :--- | :--- |
| **Inference Speed** | **~31.5 tokens/sec** |
| **Search Depth** | **k=20 (Hybrid Context Split)** |
| **Vector Store** | **ChromaDB (Persistent)** |
| **Embedding Model** | **nomic-embed-text** |

---

## 📂 Project Structure
To ensure the paths in the scripts work correctly, your directory should be organized as follows:

```text
repo-mind/
├── data/
│   └── repos/
│       └── requests/       # Clone the target repo to analyze here
├── db/                     # Created automatically by ChromaDB
├── app.py                  # The Streamlit Forensic UI & RAG Logic
├── ingest_git.py           # Dual-stream (History + Source) Ingestor
├── requirements.txt        # Project dependencies
└── README.md               # Documentation

🛠️ Step-by-Step Setup Guide

Follow these steps exactly to replicate the environment on any new system.
1. Prerequisites

    Python 3.10 or higher

    Ollama installed (Download here)

    NVIDIA GPU (Highly recommended for 30+ tok/s performance)

2. Environment Configuration

Open your terminal (PowerShell or Bash) and run:
Bash

# 1. Clone this repository
git clone <your-repo-url>
cd repo-mind

# 2. Create a Virtual Environment
python -m venv venv

# 3. Activate the Virtual Environment
# On Windows:
.\venv\Scripts\activate
# On Mac/Linux:
source venv/bin/activate

# 4. Install all dependencies
pip install -r requirements.txt

3. Prepare the Local AI Models

Repo-Mind requires the LLM and the Embedding model to be available locally:
Bash

# Pull the LLM (The Analyst)
ollama pull qwen2.5-coder:7b

# Pull the Embedding Model (The Librarian)
ollama pull nomic-embed-text

4. Prepare the Forensic Target

Place the repository you want to audit into the data/repos/ directory:
Bash

mkdir -p data/repos
cd data/repos

# Example: Auditing the 'Requests' library
git clone [https://github.com/psf/requests.git](https://github.com/psf/requests.git)
cd ../..

5. Ingestion & Execution
Bash

# Step A: Run the Dual-Stream Ingestor
# This vectorizes Git history AND current source code
python ingest_git.py

# Step B: Launch the Forensic UI
streamlit run app.py

🔍 How It Works: Forensic Hybrid RAG

Repo-Mind solves the "Vector Crowding" problem. In large repositories, thousands of historical commits often "drown out" the current source code in a standard vector search.

The Hybrid Solution: The system performs two parallel searches for every query:

    Stream A (Source): Filters specifically for hash: LATEST to grab current file implementations.

    Stream B (History): Filters for historical commits to understand the "Why" behind the code changes.

The AI then acts as a Senior Forensic Auditor, comparing the two streams to verify if a past security fix is still active or if a regression has occurred.
🔮 Future Plans

    Multi-Repo Knowledge: Cross-reference vulnerabilities across different projects simultaneously.

    Automated PR Auditing: A CI/CD integration that flags potential regressions before code is merged.

    Graph-Based RAG: Implement Knowledge Graphs to map dependencies between developers and functions over time.

    Cross-Language Support: Expand forensic parsing to Go, Rust, and JavaScript.

🤝 Technical Challenges Overcome

    Retrieval Imbalance: Implemented a custom hybrid retriever to prevent 300+ git commits from hiding the actual source code implementation.

    Hardware Optimization: Tuned the RAG chain for consumer-grade GPUs (RTX 3050) to maintain high-speed token generation and stable VRAM usage.
